On August 26, 2013, President Barack Obama awarded Staff Sergeant Ty M. Carter, U.S. Army, the Medal of Honor for his courageous actions during combat operations in Afghanistan on October 3, 2009. Carter served as a cavalry scout with Bravo Troop, 3rd Squadron, 61st Cavalry Regiment, 4th Brigade Combat Team, 4th Infantry Division. He will be the fifth living recipient to be awarded the Medal of Honor for actions in Iraq or Afghanistan. Carter's personal background includes growing up in Spokane, Washington, and claiming Antioch, California as his home. He is married to Shannon Carter and they have three children. Carter enlisted in the Army in January 2008 and has served in multiple deployments to Afghanistan. He is currently stationed at Joint Base Lewis-McChord, Washington. Carter's military decorations include the Purple Heart, Army Commendation Medal, Army Achievement Medal, and many others. The Medal of Honor is awarded to members of the Armed Forces who display exceptional bravery or self-sacrifice in the face of great risk.